    <h2 id="non-vegan-ingredients">What Makes Candy Non-Vegan? The Ingredients to Avoid</h2>

    <p>Before diving into our top picks, understanding which ingredients make candy non-vegan helps you evaluate any candy you encounter — not just the 15 on this list. The candy industry uses animal-derived ingredients in ways that are not always obvious. Gelatin is the most well-known offender, but beeswax, shellac, carmine, and dairy hide in products you might not expect.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">260</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">monthly searches for "best vegan candy" in the US in 2026, with the broader "vegan candy" keyword cluster pulling <strong>12,000+ monthly searches combined</strong>. The plant-based candy market reached $1.2 billion in 2025 and is projected to grow at 11.8% CAGR through 2030, driven by the 79.5 million vegans worldwide and the much larger flexitarian population that actively reduces animal product consumption.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Gelatin — Animal Bones & Skin</h4>
        <p>The #1 non-vegan candy ingredient. Protein from pig and cow collagen used in gummy bears, marshmallows, and chewy candies. Vegan alternatives: pectin (fruit-derived), agar (seaweed), starch (corn/tapioca).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Beeswax & Shellac — Insect Products</h4>
        <p>Beeswax is used as a coating on jelly beans and chocolate. Shellac (confectioner's glaze) is secreted by lac insects and used for shiny coatings on candy, sprinkles, and pills. Look for carnauba wax (plant-derived) as the vegan alternative.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Carmine — Crushed Insects</h4>
        <p>Red pigment (E120) made from crushed cochineal insects. Used in red and pink candies, yogurts, and cosmetics. It takes approximately 70,000 insects to produce one pound of carmine. Vegan alternative: beet juice, Red 40 (synthetic, debatable).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="warning" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Dairy — Hidden Milk Ingredients</h4>
        <p>Milk chocolate, milk powder, whey, casein, lactose, and milk fat appear in chocolate, caramels, nougat, and toffee. Even "dark chocolate" may contain milk fat. Always check ingredients — "dairy-free" label is the safest indicator.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>Beyond these clear animal-derived ingredients, three gray-area ingredients create debate within the vegan community: refined white sugar (potentially processed with bone char from cattle bones), artificial colors (historically tested on animals during FDA approval), and "natural flavors" (which could theoretically be derived from animal sources, though this is rare in candy). We cover these gray areas in detail in our <a href="/candy/is-swedish-fish-vegan/">Swedish Fish vegan analysis</a>.</p>

