    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vegan Candy</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What makes candy non-vegan?</summary>
      <p>Common non-vegan candy ingredients: gelatin (animal bones/skin), beeswax (insect product), shellac/confectioner's glaze (insect secretion), carmine (crushed insects for red color), dairy (milk, whey, casein), and eggs. Gray areas: refined sugar (potentially bone-char processed), artificial colors (historically animal-tested), and undisclosed natural flavors.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is dark chocolate vegan?</summary>
      <p>Pure dark chocolate (cacao + cocoa butter + sugar) is vegan, but many commercial dark chocolate products contain milk fat or milk powder. Always check ingredients. Reliably vegan brands: Hu Kitchen, Endangered Species (vegan varieties), Alter Eco (vegan varieties), Enjoy Life.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are Skittles vegan?</summary>
      <p>Skittles removed gelatin in 2009 and contain no direct animal ingredients. However, they contain sugar (potential bone char) and synthetic colors (animal testing history). Dietary vegans generally consider them acceptable; strict ethical vegans may avoid them. Not certified vegan.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are Oreos vegan?</summary>
      <p>Oreos contain no direct animal ingredients but are made on shared equipment with dairy products. Oreo's own website says they are "not suitable for vegans" due to milk cross-contact. For strictly vegan sandwich cookies, try Back to Nature or Newman-O's.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the best vegan chocolate?</summary>
      <p>Hu Chocolate Gems (best overall — 3 ingredients, no refined sugar), Unreal PB Cups (best peanut butter cups — Fair Trade, 5 ingredients), Endangered Species 72% (best value — Fair Trade, 10% to wildlife), Alter Eco Truffles (best premium — organic, compostable packaging).</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are gummy vitamins vegan?</summary>
      <p>Most mainstream gummy vitamins (Vitafusion, Nature Made, Centrum) contain gelatin. Vegan alternatives include MaryRuth Organics (all vegan), Hilo Nutrition, and select OLLY products labeled "vegan." Look for "pectin" in ingredients and "vegan" on the label. See our <a href="/vegan-gummies/">vegan supplement guides</a>.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How can I tell if candy is vegan?</summary>
      <p>Three-step check: (1) Look for "Certified Vegan" logo. (2) If no certification, read ingredients for gelatin, beeswax, shellac, carmine, dairy, eggs. (3) For gray areas (sugar, colors, natural flavors), decide your personal threshold. USDA Organic certification guarantees sugar was not bone-char refined.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the best vegan candy brands?</summary>
      <p>Surf Sweets (best gummies), SmartSweets (best low-sugar), Hu Kitchen (best chocolate), Unreal (best chocolate candy), YumEarth (best for kids), Black Forest (best value), Project 7 (best mission-driven). All use plant-based gelling agents, clean sugar sources, and natural colors.</p>
    </details>

